node.title: Video of Lauren Boebert Leading Crowd in 'Let's Go Brandon' Chant Goes Viral
node.description: The video is believed to be from November, soon after the Colorado congresswoman first revealed her "Let's Go Brandon" dress.

node.title: Corruption watchdog gets former MP Phil Edman's laptop after stripper and sex trip expenses probe
node.description: WA's Corruption and Crime Commission finally gets access to more than 500,000 documents from former Liberal MP Phil Edman's laptop as part of a long-running misconduct probe.

node.title: The Elusive Truth Behind the Attack on a French Soccer Star
node.description: The assault of a top women’s player made headlines, with masked men, a metal bar and a teammate arrested. But weeks later, new details suggest the original story might have been wrong.

node.title: China Ambassador Says U.S. Wasn't Even Invited to Olympics

node.title: Better Flooded With Negative Reviews After Mass Firing Over Zoom—'CEO Is a Garbage Person'
node.description: The mortgage lender startup's Trustpilot page received numerous one-star reviews after workers were fired over a brief, one-way video call.

node.title: A Vaccine Mandate for Private Employees, but Will It Last?
node.description: The mandate, set to take effect just before Mayor Bill de Blasio leaves office, would apply to workers at about 184,000 businesses.

node.title: Florida Man Finds Boa Constrictor Hiding Inside His New Couch
node.description: Officers with the Clearwater Police Department extracted the five foot snake.

node.title: Shooters called in as rabbits plague Parliament House
node.description: Public servants in Canberra step up efforts to kill rabbits near Parliament House by employing professional shooters.

node.title: Resource Management Act amendment passes second reading
node.description: A bill making it easier for landowners to build in the backyards of the country's biggest cities has passed its second reading.

node.title: US diplomats to boycott 2022 Beijing Winter Olympics

node.title: Bannon's lawyers balk at government's push for a speedy trial

node.title: New Covid Pills Offer Hope as Omicron Looms

node.title: In Chicago, a New Approach to Gay and Bisexual Men With Prostate Cancer

node.title: Instagram Says Parental Controls Will Arrive in March
node.description: Adam Mosseri, the head of the company, is expected to face questions from lawmakers this week about whether social media harms children.

node.title: Ahead of Biden’s Democracy Summit, China Says: We’re Also a Democracy
node.description: Beijing argues that its system represents a distinctive form of democracy, one that has dealt better than the West with challenges like the pandemic.

node.title: Sydney Opera House illuminates life of acting legend David Gulpilil in posthumous tribute
node.description: One of Australia’s greatest ever actors, David Gulpilil, has lit up the sails of the Sydney Opera House as the nation continues to pay tribute to the late Northern Territory movie star’s life and films.

node.title: St Basil's operators ask to be excused from giving evidence at coronial inquest into COVID deaths
node.description: The operators of the St Basil's nursing home in Melbourne ask the coroner to excuse them from giving evidence at an inquest into the deaths of 50 residents in a COVID-19 outbreak last year on the grounds they might incriminate themselves.

node.title: PM denounces comments made by George Christensen on conspiracy theorist's show
node.description: Prime Minister Scott Morrison denounces comments made by George Christensen on an American conspiracy theorist's online show, which Labor describe as "borderline treasonous".

node.title: Trevor Noah Suggests Sending Marjorie Taylor Greene to Beijing
node.description: “If you want to get back at China, you have Marjorie Taylor Greene in the stands,” Noah said of the U.S. diplomatic boycott of the Olympics.

node.title: National MPs align themselves with Luxon's new-page philosophy

node.title: 80% schools recorded surplus after funding increase

node.title: Mayor opposed to vaccine mandates may have to work from home
node.description: The days could be numbered for the Thames-Coromandel District mayor Sandra Goudie chairing meetings in person.

node.title: Wrongly jailed man feared being raped by inmate after being told to shave legs, court told
node.description: A man suing a Federal Court judge who wrongly jailed him for contempt during divorce proceedings, says his time in jail has left him traumatised and unable to work.

node.title: Police to set up two checkpoints at Auckland-Northland border

node.title: Texas Highway Department Says 'Let's Go Brandon' Road Sign is Not Theirs

node.title: 'We are going to bring every one of them home here': Aboriginal ancestral remains laid to rest as museum says sorry
node.description: After decades of pain and anguish for Kaurna people, the first repatriations of Aboriginal ancestral remains have been laid to rest on Country, with the SA Museum apologising for holding 4,600 Aboriginal remains over the past 165 years.

node.title: A Supreme Court storm is brewing for American women
node.description: Since 2016 a wave of abortion bans in the US take aim at the landmark 1973 Supreme Court decision that guaranteed abortion as a constitutional right. Now a new case in the US Supreme Court is the most significant threat to abortion rights in the US in decades.

node.title: Proposals for changes to political donations released
node.description: The government quietly released a number of proposals, which are now out for public feedback.

node.title: Can Germany’s New Chancellor Revive the Left in Europe?
node.description: Olaf Scholz wants to win back workers who defected to the populist far right. Success could make him a model for Social Democrats everywhere.

node.title: Myanmar court sentences Suu Kyi to four years in jail
node.description: Ousted Myanmar leader Aung San Suu Kyi has been sentenced to four years in prison, in the first in a series of verdicts that could jail her for life.
